# Final skim-read rewrite

Do not inspect new artifacts unless you need to resolve an inconsistency in the current
findings. Your job is to make the final report fast to skim while preserving the same
substantive concerns.

Rewrite the final report so each finding passes this bar:
- the title is at most 18 words, preferably 14 or fewer, and names the concrete problem;
- the title must be understandable by itself in the UI: no acronyms, no project shorthand,
  no internal labels, and no multi-clause sentence;
- `context` exists and has exactly two short paragraphs separated by a blank line;
- paragraph 1 of `context` explains the relevant claim, result, or comparison in plain
  words and why it matters to the project;
- paragraph 2 of `context` explains the key setup/evidence needed to judge the concern;
- neither context paragraph is a one-sentence stub; each should usually be 45-90 words;
- each context paragraph must have at least two sentences;
- before outputting, split each context paragraph into sentences and count them; if a
  paragraph has one sentence, add a second plain sentence that explains why the claim
  matters or what evidence points to the problem;
- a semicolon-heavy single sentence does not count as two sentences;
- `issue` states the concrete problem directly, without redoing all the background, and
  should usually be 45-95 words;
- for comparison failures, `issue` says what each side was allowed to see, use, or assume;
- `issue` is normally 2-4 short sentences and never over 100 words;
- `mechanism` is the "Why it matters" section and starts with the affected claim, number,
  or takeaway;
- `mechanism` says what the reader would wrongly believe if they trusted the original
  headline or number;
- `mechanism` is 2-3 short sentences, at least 45 words, and never over 95 words;
- acronyms and project-specific shorthand are defined immediately in plain words in
  `issue`/`mechanism`, or are kept only in `location`;
- file names and run-internal labels appear in `location`, not as unexplained prose;
- audit-process jargon such as "affordance", "contract", "reader-facing", "topline", and
  "provenance" does not appear;
- the wording uses concrete terms like "training setup", "evaluation setup", "required
  access", "main result", and "what the report claims".

Before outputting, count the words in every title. Rewrite any title with more than 18
words. Replace title acronyms with plain phrases, for example "prompt-based false-fact
tool" instead of `PFF`, "per-fact document fine-tuning" instead of `SDF`, "supervised
fine-tuning" instead of `SFT`, "neural lie detection" instead of `NLA`, and "out-of-
distribution" instead of `OOD`.

Preserve the same concern levels, locations, confidence values, and substantive findings
unless the evidence clearly requires a change. Keep distinct substantive findings distinct:
do not merge separate concerns into one broader finding. If one issue is about a weak
baseline and another is about one condition receiving extra information, both must remain
visible. Output only the orientation and a single parseable ```json findings block with the
schema (`title`, `concern`, `location`, `context`, `issue`, `mechanism`, `confidence`).
